4.2.1 Experiment Results on the S3DIS Dataset
Table 2 summarizes the semantic segmentation performance on S3DIS Area 5. Without pre-training, PointSS achieves 73.8±0.4% mean Intersection over Union (mIoU), achieving competitive performance among compared methods. To assess the reliability of our results, we conduct eight independent training runs with different random seeds. One-sample t-tests comparing the PointSS mean against baselines yield: t(7)=2.90, p=0.012 vs. PTv3 (73.4%); t(7)=2.14, p=0.035 vs. Pamba (73.5%). While the margins are modest (+0.4% over PTv3, +0.3% over Pamba), PointSS delivers this competitive performance with substantially lower computational cost (Section 4.4) while retaining the linear time complexity of SSMs.

4.2.3 Experiment Results on the nuScenes Dataset
To evaluate the generalization capability of PointSS on outdoor LiDAR data, we conduct experiments on the nuScenes validation set. As shown in Table 4, PointSS achieves 81.0±0.4% mIoU, outperforming both Transformer-based methods (PTv3: 80.4%, SphereFormer: 79.5%) and SSM-based methods (Pamba: 80.4%). Statistical analysis over 5 independent runs confirms that PointSS significantly outperforms PTv3 (p=0.019, paired t-test), demonstrating that the geometry-aware multi-scale design of PointSS generalizes effectively from indoor scenes to outdoor autonomous driving scenarios, where point clouds exhibit different characteristics such as larger spatial extent and sparser density.

