6.4 Key hyperparameters (e.g., scale constraint factors) appear to be manually designed and seem sensitive, lacking robustness analysis or automatic tuning schemes.
Response: We thank the reviewer for this insightful observation. We address both the robustness concern and the manual design issue.
(1) Robustness analysis. As shown in the revised Table 10, we evaluate nine configurations of α across three scales. Performance remains highly stable when α follows a monotonically increasing pattern from fine to coarse scales: configurations (0.3,0.5,0.7), (0.3,0.6,0.9), and (0.3,0.7,0.9) yield 73.3%–73.8% mIoU, with variation below 0.5%. Varying α ∈ [0.2, 0.4] with other scales fixed produces 73.2%–73.3% mIoU, confirming that exact values within a reasonable range are not critical. Importantly, only physically inconsistent configurations degrade significantly: reversing the scale ordering (0.9,0.6,0.3) drops performance to 66.5%, which is consistent with the design principle that fine scales. require rapid state decay (small α) to capture local detail, while coarse scales require slow decay (large α) to preserve global context.
(2) Automatic tuning. The current manual specification of α is acknowledged as a limitation. As stated in the revised Conclusion, we will explore learning α as a per-layer trainable parameter via standard backpropagation in future work.
